# Trash Deletion Isolation

All record deletions for trashable modules MUST go through **deletionService**. Controllers must NEVER call `Model.deleteOne()`, `findByIdAndDelete()`, or `Model.remove()` directly on trashable models.

## Trashable Modules

- people
- organizations
- deals
- tasks
- events
- items
- responses (non-audit, non-submitted FormResponse only)

## Correct Pattern

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
const deletionService = require('../services/deletionService');

// User clicks "Delete" → move to trash
const result = await deletionService.moveToTrash({
  moduleKey: 'deals',
  recordId: req.params.id,
  organizationId: req.user.organizationId,
  userId: req.user._id,
  appKey: 'SALES',
  reason: req.body?.reason
});

if (!result.ok) {
  if (result.blocked) {
    return res.status(400).json({
      success: false,
      blocked: true,
      dependencies: result.dependencies,
      message: result.message
    });
  }
  return res.status(400).json({ success: false, message: result.message });
}

return res.json({ success: true, message: 'Moved to trash' });
```

## Do NOT Use

```javascript
// ❌ BAD
await Deal.findByIdAndDelete(req.params.id);
await deal.deleteOne();
await Task.deleteOne({ _id: req.params.id });
```

## Exceptions (Non-Trashable)

These modules may use hard delete:

- Users (deactivate only, not delete)
- Audit form responses (archive/invalidate)
- Automation rules (soft delete via enabled=false)
- ModuleDefinition, Role, Group (system config)
- ImportHistory, DemoRequest (admin cleanup)

